  "doc_id": "17412",
  "text": "In recent years, in both mice and humans, the placenta has emerged as an important source of 5-HT, that can directly impact fetal brain development . In our study, the impact of maternal low-protein diet on 5-HT was more pronounced in the placenta and fetal brain than in the dam. This supports the proposal that the placenta is cannibalised in response to maternal food deprivation to provide nutrients and substrates for the developing hypothalamus [CITATION_1] . We observed an association between levels of placental 5-HT and fetal brain 5-HT at E16.5 -the time-point at which 5-HT fibres can be detected in the hypothalamus and both exogenous and endogenous sources of 5-HT contribute to fetal 5-HT synthesis [CITATION_2] . Increased 5-HT production within the placenta might contribute to raised 5-HT levels in fetal brains from low-protein dams. Maternal tryptophan levels have also been reported to influence central 5-HT levels in the offspring and maternal peripheral 5-HT proved to be important for offspring neurodevelopment [CITATION_3] . This suggests that both maternal and placental tryptophan/ 5-HT metabolism are part of an important molecular pathway for fetal programming of the 5-HT system and brain development.",
